10000nam a22012255i 9780812204308DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013948901  a(OCoLC)979753967  a97808122043087 a10.9783/97808122043082doi  a(DE-B1597)449380  a(OCoLC)793012556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aBUS0540002bisacsh04aThe American Mortgage System :bCrisis and Reform /ced. by Marvin M. Smith, Susan M. Wachter. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b48 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe City in the Twenty-First Century00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Crisis: Origins and Solutions -- tChapter 1 The Secondary Market for Housing Finance in the United States: A Brief Overview -- tChapter 2 Reasonable People Did Disagree: Optimism and Pessimism About the U.S. Housing Market Before the Crash -- tChapter 3 Exploring the Determinants of High-Cost Mortgages to Homeowners in Low- and Moderate-Income Neighborhoods -- tChapter 4 Implications of the Housing Market Bubble for Sustainable Homeownership -- tChapter 5 A Framework for Consumer Protection in Home Mortgage Lending -- tPART II. Community Impact -- tChapter 6 A Profile of the Mortgage Crisis in a Low- and Moderate-Income Community -- tChapter 7 Constructive Credit: Revisiting the Performance of Community Reinvestment Act Lending During the Subprime Crisis -- tChapter 8 Navigating the Housing Downturn and Financial Crisis: Home Appreciation and Equity Accumulation Among Community Reinvestment Homeowners -- tChapter 9 The Community Reinvestment Act: Evaluating Past Performance and Reviewing Options for Reform -- tPART III. Reforming the Financial Architecture -- tChapter 1 0 Information Failure and the U.S. Mortgage Crisis -- tChapter 11 The Expanding Financial Safety Net: The Dodd-Frank Act as an Exercise in Denial and Cover-Up -- tChapter 12 A Private Lender Cooperative Model for Residential Mortgage Finance -- tChapter 13 Improving U.S. Housing Finance Through Reform of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac: A Framework for Evaluating Alternatives -- tChapter 1 4 Some Thoughts on What to Do with Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac -- tChapter 15 The Road Not Taken: Our Failure in Redoing the Financial Architecture -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSuccessful home ownership requires the availability of appropriate mortgage products. In the years leading up to the collapse of the housing market, home buyers frequently accepted mortgages that were not only wrong for them but catastrophic for the economy as a whole. When the housing market bubble burst, so did a cornerstone of the American dream for many families. Restoring the promise of this dream requires an unflinching inspection of lending institutions and the right tools to repair the structures that support solid home purchases. The American Mortgage System: Crisis and Reform focuses on the causes of the housing market collapse and proposes solutions to prevent another rash of foreclosures.Edited by two leaders in the field of real estate and finance, Susan M. Wachter and Marvin M. Smith, The American Mortgage System examines key elements of the mortgage meltdown. The volume's contributors address the influence of the Community Reinvestment Act, which is often blamed for the crisis. They uncover how the government-sponsored enterprises Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac invested outside the housing market with disastrous results. They present surprising information about low-income borrowers and the strengths of local banks. This collection of thoughtful studies includes extensive analysis of loan practices and the creation of unstable mortgage securities, presenting data largely unavailable until now. More than a critique, The American Mortgage System offers solutions to the problems facing the future of American home ownership, including identifying asset price bubbles, calculating risk, and preventing discrimination in lending.Measured yet timely and by turns provocative, The American Mortgage System provides a careful assessment of a troubled but indispensable part of the economic and social structure of the United States. This book is a sound investment for economists, urban planners, and all who shape public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFinancial crises -- United States. 0aMortgage loans -- United States. 0aSecondary mortgage market -- United States. 0aSubprime mortgage loans -- United States. 4aEconomics. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Real Estate / General.2bisacsh  aBusiness.  aEconomics.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aBarr, Michael S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalem, Paul S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDechario, Toni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDokko, Jane K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllen, Ingrid Gould, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngel, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzpatrick, IV, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoote, Christopher L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerardi, Kristopher S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKane, Edward J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeys, Benjamin J., ec